Good morning, y'all. My name is Simon. I write open source R packages at Posit,

00:00:07.360 --> 00:00:10.160
and I want to show you how to speed up your tidymodels code.

00:00:13.120 --> 00:00:18.559
So to start off, we'll work through an example predictive modeling problem in this talk.

00:00:19.200 --> 00:00:25.040
We're working with a binary outcome, so we're deciding between the values yes or no for a given

00:00:25.040 --> 00:00:33.520
variable, and we're working with a data set that is 100,000 rows and 18 columns. So that first

00:00:33.520 --> 00:00:39.759
column is the binary outcome that we're trying to predict, and the remaining 17 we can use to try

00:00:39.759 --> 00:00:47.040
to predict the value of that outcome. We're working with 100,000 rows, so we're not necessarily in

00:00:47.040 --> 00:00:52.320
big data territory yet, depending on your definition, but not a trivial amount of data

00:00:52.320 --> 00:00:59.040
either. And we have a mix of numbers and categorical variables as predictors. So my

00:00:59.040 --> 00:01:05.599
question is, how long will it take to tune a boosted tree model using tidymodels on my laptop?

00:01:06.480 --> 00:01:12.879
If you're not familiar with a boosted tree, a boosted tree is a model type that's analogous

00:01:12.879 --> 00:01:18.639
to something like a logistic regression or a decision tree, but it's particularly computationally

00:01:18.639 --> 00:01:25.839
intensive to train. And when I say tune that model, we're going to try out multiple

00:01:26.639 --> 00:01:31.919
potential argument values to the training function and see which ones stick.

00:01:34.959 --> 00:01:40.400
So we're going to choose between two different modeling approaches here. If I just use all of

00:01:40.400 --> 00:01:47.199
the default values in tidymodels, I use the default engine or the underlying package that

00:01:47.199 --> 00:01:53.440
will actually carry out the model fit. That's called XGBoost. That takes three hours and 40

00:01:53.440 --> 00:02:01.360
minutes. If I'm working with 100,000 rows, my expectation, if I'm just modeling a binary

00:02:01.360 --> 00:02:08.479
outcome on tabular data, is that we should be able to iterate a lot faster on that than three

00:02:08.479 --> 00:02:16.080
hours and 40 minutes. So the error metric I have that we're using in this example is the area

00:02:16.080 --> 00:02:22.479
under the ROC curve that takes values between zero and one. And in this particular default

00:02:22.479 --> 00:02:32.320
modeling approach resulted in this value. Today, I'm going to show you that you can cut down on

00:02:32.320 --> 00:02:41.440
the time required to tune this model by over 99% while sacrificing only 0.03% of your predictive

00:02:41.440 --> 00:02:49.199
performance. And you can do that by just making four high-level changes that with tidymodels only

00:02:49.199 --> 00:02:56.000
require seven lines of code. So when I outline these four changes, this is going to go pretty

00:02:56.000 --> 00:03:02.479
fast. Don't feel like you need to take notes all the way through. I'm going to share resources at

00:03:02.479 --> 00:03:07.919
the end of this talk. But if you're feeling eager, you can also just hop to the link shown at the

00:03:07.919 --> 00:03:21.919
bottom of this slide, github.com slash simonpcouch slash rpharma dash 24. Okay, so quickly some

00:03:21.919 --> 00:03:28.720
background on what tidymodels is actually doing when you go to fit a model. So at the top of this

00:03:28.720 --> 00:03:35.119
diagram, I have this code reading fit, boost tree. We're modeling the outcome as a function of all of

00:03:35.119 --> 00:03:41.759
the predictors, and we're using this data set called d. What actually happens in this situation

00:03:41.759 --> 00:03:48.960
is that tidymodels, the tidymodels team doesn't actually implement any of the model training

00:03:48.960 --> 00:03:56.800
or prediction code that we're running. There are a lot of our users who are intimately familiar

00:03:56.800 --> 00:04:02.080
with the details of different statistical models, and we trust those practitioners to be the ones

00:04:02.240 --> 00:04:08.160
to implement the modeling code. What we do as the tidymodels team is put a wrapper on top of that

00:04:08.880 --> 00:04:15.440
training and prediction code that unifies the interface. So this code fits a boosted tree model,

00:04:16.320 --> 00:04:21.679
the code to fit a logistic regression or a decision tree or all sorts of other model types,

00:04:21.679 --> 00:04:28.239
and the code to do so with all sorts of different modeling packages is exactly the same regardless.

00:04:28.799 --> 00:04:35.279
So the first step is that we translate that inputted code into a code that the modeling

00:04:35.279 --> 00:04:40.880
engine will understand. So the default modeling engine for a boosted tree in tidymodels is

00:04:40.880 --> 00:04:47.760
actually boost. That code will take some amount of time to evaluate, and it will return its result

00:04:47.760 --> 00:04:55.920
back to tidymodels. Tidymodels situates it in a common user interface, and the fit function

00:04:56.880 --> 00:05:04.640
returns its value. So this code takes some amount of time to run. I've shown the portions of that

00:05:04.640 --> 00:05:10.959
evaluation time that the tidymodels team is responsible for in green, and I've shown the

00:05:10.959 --> 00:05:16.079
portions that the modeling engine is responsible for that the tidymodels team can't necessarily

00:05:16.079 --> 00:05:24.320
control in orange. In reality, the green portions here are on the order of like a couple milliseconds,

00:05:24.320 --> 00:05:32.079
and they don't tend to scale with the size of the data. The orange segment here is, again,

00:05:33.200 --> 00:05:38.399
the implementer of the modeling engine is responsible for how long that code takes to run,

00:05:39.040 --> 00:05:43.679
and that tends to scale with the size of the data. So larger data sets take longer to fit.

00:05:43.679 --> 00:05:52.320
So if I'm tuning a boosted tree, that analogous diagram in that situation is that we're fitting

00:05:52.320 --> 00:05:59.679
many, many models, and we're doing the translation step on either side, but the tuning process

00:05:59.679 --> 00:06:05.440
requires trying out a bunch of different arguments to the boosted tree model and fitting it to a

00:06:05.440 --> 00:06:10.720
bunch of different subsets. So in this example, we're trying to do a translation step on a

00:06:10.720 --> 00:06:15.519
bunch of different subsets. So in this example, we're trying out 10 possible boosted tree

00:06:16.880 --> 00:06:23.920
argument settings, and for each of those 10 argument settings, we're fitting that model

00:06:23.920 --> 00:06:30.079
to 10 different subsets of the data. That's called resampling. So there's 100 model fits

00:06:30.079 --> 00:06:35.679
total happening here. This tuning process that we're visualizing right now is the one that took

00:06:35.679 --> 00:06:43.040
three hours and 41 minutes. So how can we cut down on the time to tune that model by over 99%?

00:06:44.959 --> 00:06:48.799
The first thing that we can do is distribute our computations across

00:06:48.799 --> 00:06:55.839
CPU cores. So modern laptops are pretty incredible. Many have many, many cores. The

00:06:55.839 --> 00:07:03.200
most recent MacBooks are looking at double digits. I'm working on a laptop right now that's four

00:07:03.200 --> 00:07:11.600
years old, and I can use four CPU cores at a single time. So instead of fitting 100 models

00:07:11.600 --> 00:07:19.839
in a row one at a time, we can fit four at a time, and best case scenario, cut down on the amount of

00:07:19.839 --> 00:07:28.160
time to tune this boosted tree by four. In tidy models, all you need to make this happen is one

00:07:28.160 --> 00:07:34.720
line of code. If you're familiar with the future framework, tidy models integrates with future,

00:07:34.720 --> 00:07:39.760
and so this is just future code as it is, and this one line of code will tell tidy models

00:07:39.760 --> 00:07:44.079
all it needs to know about how to distribute computations on your laptop.

00:07:48.480 --> 00:07:53.200
Next, I'm going to pick a modeling engine that is particularly well suited to the modeling

00:07:53.200 --> 00:07:59.519
problem that I'm working on. So by default, the modeling engine in our boosted tree case

00:07:59.519 --> 00:08:07.200
is XGBoost. I happen to know, based on the way that this data set that we're using as an example

00:08:07.200 --> 00:08:14.959
looks, that a modeling engine called LightGBM might fit faster on that example. So we've cut

00:08:14.959 --> 00:08:19.920
down on the width of this diagram by a pretty significant factor already, both by distributing

00:08:19.920 --> 00:08:27.359
our computations across four CPU cores and choosing a model that fits faster than the default

00:08:27.359 --> 00:08:35.520
model. It's not always the case that a given modeling engine will fit faster than another,

00:08:37.200 --> 00:08:40.559
regardless of the data context that you're working with. There are situations where

00:08:40.559 --> 00:08:45.919
XGBoost is more performant, but this is a matter of building your intuition through practice,

00:08:45.919 --> 00:08:49.840
and I'll show you at the end of this talk through some resources that I'll share with you.

00:08:52.880 --> 00:08:57.119
In tidy models, there's no sort of syntax foo that you need to do

00:08:57.119 --> 00:09:01.039
to translate your fitting code from one modeling engine to another.

00:09:01.039 --> 00:09:05.359
All you need to do is set the engine argument to a different value.

00:09:05.919 --> 00:09:11.599
Next, we can use something called the sub-model trick. This is the third modification that I'll

00:09:11.599 --> 00:09:16.559
talk about. The sub-model trick is a bit of a rabbit hole, so we're not going to go too deep

00:09:16.559 --> 00:09:22.479
down that rabbit hole. But the idea here is that we can evaluate many more models than we actually

00:09:22.479 --> 00:09:28.400
fit. The sub-model trick enables you to fit a single model and predict across several of them,

00:09:29.200 --> 00:09:34.159
and the tidy models has some tricky stuff going on in the back end to make sure that we

00:09:34.159 --> 00:09:40.640
enable that as often as we can. The way that you can explicitly opt into that sub-model trick as

00:09:40.640 --> 00:09:50.000
a user is by using a function called grid regular, and using a regular grid will enable the sub-model

00:09:50.400 --> 00:09:56.159
trick. In cases where you're just tuning a single model parameter, this just works if it's

00:09:56.159 --> 00:10:01.280
available, so there's nothing you need to do as a user. But this is for added lines of code here.

00:10:05.119 --> 00:10:09.039
And the fourth technique that we'll use is something called raising. So, I said earlier

00:10:09.039 --> 00:10:13.679
that we're training or we're choosing between 10 different possible values,

00:10:13.679 --> 00:10:19.359
and we're doing so by fitting each of those 10 different possible argument values to 10

00:10:19.359 --> 00:10:27.440
different subsets of the data. What happens in practice is that we can fit each of those 10

00:10:27.440 --> 00:10:36.239
possible models to 3 of those subsets, or even 2, and that will give us enough information to realize

00:10:36.719 --> 00:10:44.400
to 3 of those subsets, or even 2, and that will give us enough information to realize that some

00:10:44.400 --> 00:10:49.840
of those models are much more likely to be the most performant, the best possible model we have

00:10:49.840 --> 00:10:56.559
access to, than others. And so, instead of continuing to train all of those models that

00:10:56.559 --> 00:11:02.880
we're pretty sure are not going to outperform the most performant, and we can bound that pretty sure

00:11:03.679 --> 00:11:08.719
by a significance level, we can just go ahead and give up on those and not fit them to the

00:11:08.719 --> 00:11:15.119
remaining 8 or 7 or 6 resamples, and that will cut down on our time to tune even further.

00:11:18.239 --> 00:11:21.599
In tidy models, to make this happen, all you need to do is change one line of code.

00:11:22.400 --> 00:11:29.599
That default grid search can be transitioned to racing with a repeated measures ANOVA model.

00:11:29.679 --> 00:11:34.080
That's called tune race ANOVA, and that can cut down on your time to tune as well.

00:11:36.640 --> 00:11:41.919
And so, altogether, we started with this tuning process that fitted every possible model in

00:11:41.919 --> 00:11:47.760
sequence, and each of those model fits took a good while, and that resulted in a training process that

00:11:47.760 --> 00:11:54.080
was 3 hours and 40 minutes. That will really hinder your ability to iterate as you develop

00:11:54.080 --> 00:12:01.919
models interactively. We can make four small changes that require changes to seven lines of

00:12:01.919 --> 00:12:08.000
code, give or take, depending on how liberally you add spaces, to transition that code to run

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:14.159
in 90 seconds, and you don't have to sacrifice predictive performance on your way to doing so.

